        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Shearing increases or decreases a color component by an amount proportional to another color component.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For example, consider the transformation where the red component is increased by one half the value of the blue component.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Under such a transformation, the color (0.2, 0.5, 1) would become (0.7, 0.5, 1).</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The new red component is 0.2 + (1/2)(1) = 0.7.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Example</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example constructs an <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Drawing.Image&gt;</ph> object from the file ColorBars4.bmp.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Then the code applies the shearing transformation described in the preceding paragraph to each pixel in the image.</source>
        </trans-unit>
